identificationRemarks: Hair-cap Moss- four in Anchorage area. Juniper Haircap (P. juniperinum)- stems are reddish with grey-green leaves that have a distinctive red-brown tip. Usually on mineral soil. Stems brownish tomentose only near base; capsules to 2 times longer than broad. vs. Common Haircap (P. commune)- leaves w/ green tip w/o long hyaline awn On moist organic soils. vs. White-awned haircap (P. piliferum)- stems reddish. leaf sheaths ovate, abruptly contracted to a long green tip w/ hyaline awn. sites that are open, dry and acidic, such as in shallow soil vs. Polytrichum strictum- Folded leaf margins and short reddish leaf tips. Stems densely whitish tomentose; capsules cubic

identificationRemarks: The Flora of North America (http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=250100465) and Panarctic Flora consider the arctic plants to be Spiraea stevenii. Murray and Elven in the Panarctic Flora write: Uttal (1973) concluded that the name Spiraea beauverdiana, previously often applied for the arctic plants (e.g., by Hultén 1968a), has been misapplied and in its strict meaning refers to the distinctly non-arctic S. betulifolia Pall. var. aemiliana (C.K. Schneid.) Hara 1952 described from the Riishiri Islands in northern Japan. Several differential characters are cited. Spiraea stevenii is now generally accepted to be the correct name for the arctic plants.
